title: Pipe/round-bar clamp with hinge and captive nut

description.text:
This OpenSCAD script will generate a 2 part hinged clamp which can be used to attach things to pipes or round bars such as handlebars, pencils, canes etc.
The script is fully parametric and only requires you to input the diameter of your pipe, how thick you want the clamp to be and what sized nuts/bolts filament (for use as a hinge pin) you want to use Radial tolerances and other values can be altered from stock if you want
The top, bottom or both can be optionally generated by changing a boolean control variable
Mouse ears can be added easily by changing a boolean control variable @author Mark Gaffney

remixed_from.title: Mostly Printed CNC -Add On- Dewalt DW660 Mount - updated-

description.text:
DESIGNED FOR USE WITH THE STANDARD UNIVERSAL TOOL MOUNT THAT IS AN INCLUDED PART OF THE MPCNC DESIGN.

BEFORE YOU START...this setup requires that you remove the "tool free" spindle lock from your DW660 and replace it with the "DW660_nose_cover." I you don't want to or can't do this, then stop now.

These parts should be printed with 50% infill and 3 perimeters. The only part that should require supports is the "dust_shoe_with_brush." PLA at 100% scale will work great and I printed at a .25mm layer height.

The vacuum comes from a shop vac that I have plumbed in my shop. The hose going from this plumbing to my MPCNC has a 1 1/4" tapered end. You may have to make an adapter for your own plumbing needs. Or post a message and I may try to design one for you to print if you ask nice.

30-40psi seems to work just fine for me on the air jet. The lower you can go, the less your compressor has to run.

You will also need:

Several feet of 1/4" polyethelene tubing to run an air line down to the spindle.
1 1/4" push connect adapter with 1/4" MPT to screw into a standard air compressor hose fitting.
1 90° elbow 1/4" push connect adapter with 1/8" NPT to screw into the "lower_mount_with_air_jet"
1 air inflation needle
2 6-32 1/2" screws
2 6-32 nylock nuts
8" 3/4" PVC "thin wall" pipe (ASTM D-2241)
Brush sold here: https://www.mcmaster.com/#catalog/123/1320/=18hi79n
Some zip ties.

I got everything but the brush at Lowes. There is a good chance I'm going to eventually design and add another variation or two of the "dust_shoe_with_brush." There's this balance between distance from the deck, tool path depth, and brush length/rigidity. The present design is general purpose and should handle a maximum cut depth of 1.5cm.

EDIT 7/16/17 Added "dust_shoe_with_brush_long." 5mm longer than the standard.
UPDATE 9/21/17 Although the original dust shoe has held up great, I am not entirely pleased with the "dust_shoe_with_brush_long," piece, so I'm removing it. I purchased some longer brush material and plan to design a shoe for it. We will see how that goes.

comments.text:
Thanks for the question! That is part of the purpose, and a good description. The air jet both cools the tool bit and blows the dust/swarf/chips out of the curf and directs it into the dust shoe, which vacuums it up. The video I posted does a better job of explaining.

description.text: This is a simple hook design.

We have wooden blinds on every window in the house and over the years we've had the clips that hold the valence boards on break until we no longer had enough to hang all of the boards. This is a replacement clip for those.

UPDATE3 NOV. 19, 2017:
hair is fixed and slightly simplified. included source BLEND and final BLEND (hair is subsurfed but body is not). could've saved a few polygons on the headband. eyeballs are 1xSS, the rest is 2xSS i think. made the upper 'cleavage window' wall thicker. forgot to edge crease the upper hair strands closest to the headband, but it shouldn't make any difference on the print. thank you for your patience.

UPDATE2 SEPT.30.2017:
-added pics of remodeled and sliced hair (last 2 pics). this head is from a different 2B model, but same approach will be applied. just a bit more tweaking w/ the tips/creases.

UPDATE SEPT.30.2017:
i figured out the hair. it wasn't really all that complicated. still testing a few things out, but it slices well... manual manifolds are key. letting netfabb or repetier do it in this case is a bad idea.

here is the necessary workflow to fix the hair:
1) separate hair layers into discrete objects using SELECT LINKED FLAT FACES at ~160
2) SOLIDIFY 2D strands to add depth always keeping an eye on non-manifold edges
3) cap hair "tubes" to create solids

never combine the hair into one object... leave them all separate, and export to STL w/ the rest of the model.

now that i know what works i just have to tris-->quads before following those 3 steps. then subsurf and clean up and sharp points and its DONE. this model will be finalized soon.

UPDATE: the body is pretty much finished. no manifold edges, everything is perfect. the hair on the other hand is a bit of a disaster. i might have to rethink/remodel it or try A2 hair if its easier to work with. i could also just 'solidify' the main hair and layer it somehow. fixed edges, smoothed gloves, connected parts resulting in 0 manifolds, added definition to bikini line, added more edge creases.

2xSS already weighs in at a hefty 40MB. i'll have to figure out the best and most efficient way to smooth the model w/o going overboard. again, not anywhere near complete, i just wanted to piece it together and gauge filesize as well as printability.

In this activity, students will use these manipulatives to find the distance the horse travels around the circular track.

In making these manipulatives, I used a cylinder to create the circular track and dropped another small cylinder in the center to create the hole. To create the horse that moves around the circle, I used a horse design that was already created from a source on tinkercad (https://www.tinkercad.com/search/?q=horse). I attached the horse to a rectangle and put a cylinder on the bottom (small enough to fit in the center hole of the circle) then grouped them together so that it was one object. I rotated the horse a little on the rectangle so that the feet did not hit the track as it moved along the circle. In creating the P attachment, I used rectangles and made sure the opening was wide enough to fit onto the circular track. I labeled it with a circle and letter P and then grouped all these items together.
CCSS

This activity will satisfy the following Common Core State Standard:
CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.HSG.C.B.5

Begin this activity by reviewing that arc length is the distance around a circle between two points (a portion of the circumference), and the formula to find arc length is
S= 2πr( θ / 360 ), S being arc length, r is the radius, and θ is the angle in degrees. Next, have students work in groups of 2 or 3 to create 3 different scenarios where the angle measure is different. Students will place the clip P anywhere on the circle and measure the angles (between the horse and point P) each time with a protractor. The radius will be measured with a ruler. Students will use the formula to calculate the arc length. After students have completed all three scenarios, they will check their results by measuring the arc length with a string.
Print these objects before class. You need one set per group, along with string.

description.text:
Helicone is an interactive sculpture by John Edmark (more info). You can buy one on Amazon. By rotating the shaft, the arms can settle into a helix, or a pinecone shape that uses (half of) the Golden Angle to fill out the space completely.

I saw a few videos of it in action and decided I wanted to try to make one. I found a few models online, but they all relied on externally visible notches for stops, which the Helicone does not exhibit. After I came up with my solution, I saw a "making of" video with some screen shots of the laser pattern which indicates that it uses a very similar mechanism.

A video of it working.

You can use the Customizer to change various dimensions and petal shape. If you download the OpenSCAD file, you can also adjust the number of slices and experiment with different functions to change the helix angle and 3D outline.

The color change in the photos/video is due to running out of black, and having to replace two slices due to breakage.

Print out two of each slice. The slice number is embossed on the underside of one petal to help keep them organized when you drop them. To assemble, thread all the slices and top and bottom caps onto a 3/16" dowel, working them around until they spin freely. Glue the bottom cap to the rod (I used a dot of superglue; be careful not to glue any other parts to the rod). You can also glue to the top cap into position if you want to prevent the parts flying off the top.

description.text:
Hey every one,

This is my first ever upload to Thingiverse so please bare with me!

I recently got into using Octopi (love it btw) and wanted to use the webcam feature. i went down to my local big box store and picked up a Logitech C270 for around 30 bucks, plugged it into the Octopi and it worked amazing right off the bat. All though i struggled on where to mount the camera. I used gorilla tape and taped it all over the place but nothing really did what i wanted it to do.

i looked here for a mount and was super pumped that there were lots that could be used. The downfall to having a custom Robo3D is that things that work for every one else dont necessarily work for you. I have an enclosure around my Robo3d which makes printing ABS a breeze, but with the enclosure comes limited space (hence the reason for the project)
(enclosure can be found here https://printedsolid.com/products/robo-3d-safety-enclosure-kit )

i located a part on here made by adamsgl (wont let me tag him) which was the original inspiration for this project. What was supposed to be a remix ended up being a full redesign

Long story short and 7 revisions later i came up with this functional design

i made the base so that if any webcam essentially could be used. i wanted it to be adjustable so that i could center the camera on the print.

If you have any questions please feel free to ask

Thanks for looking and happy printing!

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

30%

Notes:

The mount prints in 3 different parts,

  • Main body - Needs to be printed with support. There is a 1mm keeper channel on the top part of the main body this will need support, also the horizontal screw section located on the back side of the main body that will require support. The embedded screw channel is hollow to the other side so getting the support out is a breeze.

  • Camera mount - When you go to add your support make sure to add a little support under the hinge curves it really just helps keep the hinge portion round. it can be printed with out those little extra supports.

  • Mount connection - Could be printed with the same little hinge supports

As you can see by the photos it installs under the print bed glass. it fits snugly also allows some side to side movement of the mount body.

Once you get everything printed i used 2x 4-40x1/2" screws and 2 x washers that fit (sorry we didn't have metric where i live how ever the measurements are 2.7mm from thread to thread and 12 mm long) to attach the Mount connection to the Main body. They thread directly into the ABS.

To attach the Camera Mount to the Mount connection i used 2x 6/32 (3.37mm T2T x 12mm long with 2x washers to fit. (also threads into the ABS)

One other thing to note, once you get this printed and installed, i took the camera apart to adjust the focal point to be directly on the prints rather than the back of the enclosure. you can learn how to do this procedure here ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v-gYgBeiOVI )

i also use an elastic to hold the camera in, every iteration that i used to hold it in before failed. Also allows easy access to the camera if need be.

As you can see by the camera view you can clearly see the 2 screwdrivers i used to mark the back corners of the build plate.

title: Roller Bearing using Reuleaux Bearings
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Youtuber Maker's Muse (on thingiverse) showed a "ball" based on the Reuleaux triangle on his channel... and fellow 3d printing enthusiasts clamored for a bearing based on it.

His video was a good first start, and while he couldn't see any way forward, I think I might have. This is my attempt at a roller bearing using "Reuleaux" bearings.

The complete model likely cannot be printed on an FDM printer. It will pretty much require support material that can be dissolved.

This is not needed.

Print two each of the inner and outer races as well as two of the cage rings.

Print twelve each of the reuleaux bearings and the cage sections.

The cage ring has twelve indents that should allow the cage sections to register with the rings and twelve counter sunk holes for M3 counter sunk screws through each ring.

Six holes in each race are sized to 2.4 mm in diameter, this is for threading for an M3 screw. The other six holes are designed to be able to allow a counter sunk M3 screw to pass through. I have designed the two halves of each of the races to be rotated one twelfth of a rotation to allow six screws to pass in from each side and thread into the threaded portion of the other side.

The reuleaux bearings can be placed into an assembled cage and then this can be sandwiched with the inner and outer races.

My printer is currently offline to replace the damaged controller board so I have not printed it out.

Why buy a dehydrator and spend time modifying it if you already own everything needed to build your own [ fancy / overkill / g-code driven ] filament dehydrator oven ?

Needed parts :

  • 1 x arduino mega 2560 r3 board
  • 1 x ramps 1.4 board
  • 1 x 2004 LCD with encoder and SD card slot
  • 2 x 40 mm 12V fans
  • 1 x 500W ATX power supply
  • two pairs of mini tamyia connectors with 10mm silicone wire
  • two pin dupont connector with 20cm of red/black wire - for powering fans
  • three pin dupont connector with 20cm of red/back/yellow wire - for controlling the ATX power supply
  • 1 x 100k NTC thermistor
  • 1 x MK2Y 220mm round 12V PCB heated bed
  • 3 x M3x10 bolts - for securing the heatbed
  • 3 x M3 nuts - for securing the heatbed
  • 6 x M3 washers - for securing the heatbed
  • 4 x countersunk wood screws for the ramps case lid
  • 4 x countersunk wood screws for the lcd case
  • 1 x FAT32 formatted SD card - for running g-code
  • 1 x 3D printed case for arduino + ramps
  • 1 x 3D printed lcd case (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:35438)
  • 1 x round cookie box (big enough to fit the 220 mm heatbed and one spool of filament)
  • 1m of 12 AWG wire
  • 1 x self tightening electrical connector (heat resistant)

Needed tools & materials:

  • wire strippers
  • wire insulation
  • soldering tool
  • soldering wire
  • 2 mm thick cork sheet
  • glue
  • drilling machine

Needed skills:

  • basic electronics understanding
  • basic soldering skills
  • time and patience

Programming :

  • arduino 1.8 (https://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software)
  • the firmware (https://www.thingiverse.com/download:4089572)

Assembly :

  • This is more or less 3D printer hardware and if you ever assembled a kit you know already what needs to be done.
  • Pay attention to electrical wiring / soldering and also for good performance to insulation of the cookie box. Please do not solder wires that will be tighten down with screws ! Also use the mini tamyia connector pairs inverse one from another so you don't accidentally mismatch the thermistor with the 12V heating power.
  • The firmware is a little bit modified for aesthetics reasons, but otherwise a standard Repetier v 0.92.9 which i've chosen over Marlin for ease of web configuration.
  • Don't forget to PID calibrate the heatbed which is done on Repetier firmware with : "M303 P1 S70 R8" for 8 cycles at 70 degrees.
  • On the file section you will find also a zip file (https://www.thingiverse.com/download:3913246) with a demo 1m g-code sample and also 1h 2h 4h g-code samples to dry your filament at 70 degrees Celsius.

Power draw :

  • min : idle ATX power supply off, fans off : 1.5W
  • max : heating up at full power : 100W (the first 2-3 minutes)
  • med : PID controller stabilized heating : ~ 40W (the rest of the process)

Results :

  • initial ambient humidity : 40%
  • 4h for one spool of ABS : 15% humidity
  • 8h for one spool of ABS : 10% humidity

Humidity was monitored with an arduino conneted to 2 x DHT11 + 2 x DHT22 sensors.

description.text:
This adapter allows you to mount your Pentax Q in place of the eyepiece of a microscope.  
It fits any microscope with an inner tube diameter of 23mm, but you can easily modify it to fit other diameters,  
The two images on the right are of the chip from an SD card shot with the Q7 and a Konus microscope with a 10/0.25 objective lens. Illumination is with a Metz P-TTL flash with a soft box.

Slice at 0.1mm and print it in black ABS, matte if possible. No raft or supports needed.  
It fitted perfectly first time for me but it may need some trimming depending on your printer calibration.  
After completing it and making it fit paint the inside a matte black to reduce reflections that could degrade contrast.  
The upper layers have very little material so you might need to slow down the printing to allow cooling. If you use Skeinforge go to the  'Cool' tab and set a minimum layer time of 10 seconds or thereabout. You may need to experiment to find a good balance between having enough cooling and getting consistent flow (too slow speed makes blobs on my printer).

title: Vertical stand spool holder vitamined with ball bearings (608 or others)

description.text:
Here is (another) vertical spool holder using ball bearing.
I designed this one because all other I found where complicated to assemble (screw and bold needed), or lack a guide in the bearing for the spool edges.

This is designed to be assembled only by insert parts into each other by force.

The provided parts are for 608zz ball bearing. But any other models can be used, as the thing is parametrized. So it's possible to open the joined Fusion 360 model, and ajust the value to fit your ball bearing models (in Model worshop, Modify->Change parameters, use the parameters set in favorite).

Beware. Don't trust the theorical measure of your bearing: depending on manufacturer (especially for low cost china bearing), real inner and outer diameter can be different by 0.1 or 0.2mm. Use a caliper to measure them. Bearing coming from a same batch usually share the exact same error (measure one, the others should have the same size).

Low cost bearing are not an issue if you can precisely measure them. It's even recommended, as for this thing there is not enough speed or mechanical effort requiring quality bearing.

For a complete spool holder (2 stand), you'll need:

  • 4x groove printed part
  • 2x stand printed part
  • 4x ball bearing (608zz for the supplied STL)

Printer:

RenRen 3D Pro (Kossel XL)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

40%

Notes:

Printed in PLA. At least 40% infill is need to be strong enough.

Supports (everywhere) should be used for grooves, but if your printer is good enough with overhand, you can try without. Support are easy to remove.

Depending of your printer precision and filament quality, holes/axles may be too lose or too tight. If so, you can ajust your slicer settings.

  • Recommended. With recent version of Cura, the parameter horizontal expansion is great. Use a positive value (e.g 0.1) if the join is too lose, or a negative value (e.g. -0.1) if it's too tight.
  • Else, try reducing or increasing the flow of material.

After removing supports and cleaning parts:

1 - Put the ball bearing in the groove. You may need a little hammer to force it in. Watch the way: the groove has a stop on one of its side ; insert the bearing by the side without stop
2 - Put the groove + bearing in the axis of the stand, the side with stop first. Again, a little hammer may help.

Done!

Note: It'll works if you insert the groove in the wrong side. The recommended way is only to reduce risk for the groove to split of the bearing.

title: Pentax K-mount to Pentax Q adapter

description.text:
This adapter lets you use a Pentax K-mount lens with your Pentax Q.  
If the lens has an aperture ring then you can control the aperture as normal by the ring.  
If the lens does not have an aperture ring the aperture will be fully open when mounted on to this adapter.  If you don't want full aperture you can adjust it by slightly turning the lens as if unmounting form the adpater. A few degrees will fully close the aperture.  
The adapter does not have a locking pin for the lens but fits tightly enough to not need one. The lack of it also allows to change the aperture as described above.  
The adapter does not have a tripod mount, something which I intend to do when I find some time for it.

Slice at 0.1mm. Print in black ABS preferably matte. No raft or support needed. The lens side will need some trimming before it can fit properly to the lens. If you have some old lens lying about that is not so important then best to experiment with it until you get the right fit.
The camera side did not need any trimming in my case but that will depend on your printer's calibration. Once you have achieved good fit to both the camera and the lens paint the inside of the adapter a matte black and allow it to dry well. This will avoid contrast being degraded by light reflected off the inside. The reason mine is red is simply because I ran out of black filament. The upper layers have very little material so you might need to slow down the printing to allow cooling. If you use Skeinforge go to the 'Cool' tab and set a minimum layer time of 10 seconds or thereabout. You may need to experiment to find a good balance between having enough cooling and getting consistent flow (too slow speed makes blobs on my printer).

description.text:
The lockclips on Bosch cases happen to break after years of use. Therefore I needed a replacement lock for the case of the Bosch SDS Drill. The lock could be used for other things too of course.

Created with OnShape https://cad.onshape.com/documents/db4dc8b701f6258cf8c0d9ea/w/e3a6e48932eaaf0065b58047/e/8f89a93ef5f92ccec310b314

40%

Notes:

Supports is only needed for the block when you want to print it in one piece. Read the steps for more information about printing the block without supports.

Design

I designed this in OnShape but created a sketch with pencil on paper first. Dimensions are based on what I thought should work out.

Pins

To assemble this lock you need to make pins out of 3mm screws, just saw the top off and make a small incision on one side of the pin to be able to screw them into the parts.
Needed for one lock is a four 3mm screws cut-off to a length of two times 6mm and two times 10mm.

Blocks

The blocks can be sliced from 7mm for printing without support material. After printing cleanup both parts of the block and apply a tiny bit of glue before assembling.

Holes

Drill the holes to 3mm. You need four screws, rings and nuts to mount this onto the case. See the pictures for the endresult.

Make a small incision into the thread-screw The parts assembled and attached to the case Move the top over the block Press the clip down and the lock is shut! Happy drilling!

This is a mount for the Anova Precision Cooker.

Al you need is a storage box with a lid. Cut a hole in the lid of around 74mm in diameter and glue the ring in place. My box is made of polypropylene, so it is quite hard to glue.
What worked for me is high temperature hot melt, which seems to withstand the sous vide temperatures quite well. It is applied underneath the flange and some extra glue underneath the lid.

Another advantage is that no more steam or moist is getting sucked in the cooker. I read some stories that this cooker got damaged when used with an open container.

Read the note on materials below.

Happy sous vide-ing ! :-)

title: MKS SBASE v1.3 Bracket for 2020 Aluminum Extrusion

description.text:
A simple bracket I quickly whipped up in TinkerCAD to mount my MKS SBASE v1.3 controller board to my HyperCube's frame. I designed it to fit in the corner of the aluminum extrusions and didn't want something that would use a ton of plastic.

Hardware needed:
(3x) M3x10 bolts (for mounting the SBASE to the bracket)
(3x) M5x10 bolts (for mounting the bracket to the extrusions)
(3x) M5 T-Slot nuts (for securing the bolts)

As it is quite basic, and perhaps not as elegant as some brackets, I uploaded it purely for the sake of posterity; hopefully it can help at least one person out.
